In Spring Boot, @Primary sets a default bean to be injected when multiple beans of the same type exist,
while @Qualifier explicitly names the exact bean you want to inject at a specific injection point.

When both are used together, @Qualifier always overrides @Primary.

Without either annotation, having multiple beans of the same type causes Spring to throw a NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException.


sample code -

using primary 


@Component
@Primary // Sets this class as the default choice
public class EmailService implements NotificationService {
    public void send(String message) { System.out.println("Email: " + message); }
}

@Component
public class SmsService implements NotificationService {
    public void send(String message) { System.out.println("SMS: " + message); }
}


qualtifier 

@RestController
public class SpecificController {
    @Autowired
    @Qualifier("smsService") // Explicitly targets the SMS bean by its name
    private NotificationService service; // Injects SmsService
}
